# DarkForest Scenario 004 - Active Directory Enumeration & Persistence

## Overview

This scenario simulates a complete Active Directory attack sequence performed directly on the Domain Controller (DC1).

Unlike traditional attack paths involving compromised workstations, this scenario focuses on the visibility of Active Directory activity from the perspective of a Security Operations Center (SOC).

The objective is to validate Splunk detections, Sysmon telemetry, PowerShell logging and Windows Security events while documenting a realistic attacker workflow.

---

## Objectives

- Validate Active Directory authentication monitoring
- Generate PowerShell Operational logs (Event ID 4104)
- Generate Sysmon Process Creation events (Event ID 1)
- Monitor account creation and privilege modifications
- Validate Splunk dashboards and detection rules
- Produce reproducible SOC investigation scenarios

---

## Lab Environment

| Component | Description |
|-----------|-------------|
| Domain Controller | DC1 (Windows Server 2022) |
| SIEM | Splunk Enterprise |
| Logging | Sysmon + Windows Security + PowerShell Operational |
| Remote Access | Apache Guacamole (RDP) |

---

# Attack Chain

## Phase 1 - Initial Access

The attacker authenticates to DC1 using Remote Desktop through Apache Guacamole.

Expected Events

- Event ID 4624
- Interactive Logon
- Successful authentication

Dashboard Panels

- Successful Logons
- Authentication Activity
- Top Source IPs

---

## Phase 2 - Active Directory Enumeration

The attacker begins reconnaissance of the Active Directory environment.

PowerShell Commands

```powershell
Get-ADUser
Get-ADComputer
Get-ADGroup
Get-ADDomain
Get-ADForest
```

Command Prompt

```cmd
whoami
whoami /groups
hostname

net user
net user /domain

net group "Domain Admins" /domain
net accounts /domain

nltest /dsgetdc:pale.forest
```

Expected Events

- PowerShell Event ID 4104
- Sysmon Event ID 1
- LDAP Activity

Dashboard Panels

- PowerShell Activity
- Suspicious AD Commands
- Process Creation Timeline
- Top Process
- LDAP Activity

---

## Phase 3 - Account Creation

The attacker creates a new Active Directory account.

Example

```powershell
New-ADUser `
-Name "backupsvc" `
-SamAccountName backupsvc `
-AccountPassword (ConvertTo-SecureString "Password123!" -AsPlainText -Force) `
-Enabled $true
```

Expected Events

- User Creation
- Directory Service Events

Dashboard Panels

- User Management
- LDAP Activity

---

## Phase 4 - Privilege Escalation

The newly created account is added to a privileged security group.

Example

```powershell
Add-ADGroupMember `
-Identity "Domain Admins" `
-Members backupsvc
```

Expected Events

- Group Membership Modification
- Directory Service Events

Dashboard Panels

- Group Changes
- LDAP Activity

---

## Phase 5 - Validation

The attacker disconnects from the current session and authenticates using the newly created account.

Expected Events

- Event ID 4624
- Interactive Logon

Dashboard Panels

- Successful Logons
- Authentication Timeline
- Top Source IPs

---

## MITRE ATT&CK Mapping

| Phase | Technique |
|--------|-----------|
| Initial Access | T1078 - Valid Accounts |
| Discovery | T1087 - Account Discovery |
| Discovery | T1018 - Remote System Discovery |
| Discovery | T1482 - Domain Trust Discovery |
| Execution | T1059.001 - PowerShell |
| Persistence | T1136.002 - Create Domain Account |
| Privilege Escalation | T1098 - Account Manipulation |

---

# Expected Detection Coverage

The scenario validates the following telemetry:

- Windows Security Log
- Sysmon Process Creation
- Sysmon Network Connections
- PowerShell Operational Logging
- Directory Service Logs
- LDAP Activity
- Authentication Events
- Account Management Events

---

# Expected Dashboard Activity

The following DarkForest Active Directory dashboard panels should react during the scenario.

- Successful Logons
- Failed Logons (optional)
- Authentication Activity
- Top Source IPs
- PowerShell Activity
- Suspicious AD Commands
- Process Creation Timeline
- Top Process
- LDAP Activity
- User Creation
- Group Membership Changes

---

# Learning Objectives

After completing this scenario, the analyst should be able to:

- Follow an attack through multiple Windows log sources
- Correlate Security, Sysmon and PowerShell events
- Detect Active Directory reconnaissance
- Identify account creation and privilege escalation
- Validate SOC dashboards and detections
- Understand the attack lifecycle from initial authentication to persistence

